\cf2 \cb3     "idea_rank": 1,\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3     "idea_name": "Mental Health Crisis Early-Warning System: Social Media Distress Signal Monitor",\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3     "idea_summary": "The first implementation approach focuses on mining social media platforms for real-time distress signals at the neighborhood level. Using NLP models trained on mental health crisis language, the system continuously processes public posts from Twitter/X, Reddit community boards, and Nextdoor neighborhood groups, flagging surges in distress-related keywords, phrases, and sentiment patterns. These signals are aggregated by ZIP code and combined with CDC BRFSS baseline mental health prevalence data to produce a weekly distress index. When a ZIP code's index exceeds a threshold, the system alerts crisis coordinators and community health workers to increase outreach in that area. The approach is purely signal-side \'97 it detects demand before it becomes a formal crisis call, operating in the earliest warning layer of the system.",\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3     "information_story": "It is a Tuesday night in Rainier Valley, Seattle. Across dozens of neighborhood Facebook groups and Nextdoor threads, residents are posting about job losses, sleepless nights, and feeling like there is no point anymore. Each post is isolated \'97 one person venting to a small local group. No crisis worker sees the pattern. No 211 operator knows that in this specific ZIP code, posts containing words like 'hopeless', 'can't go on', and 'nobody cares' have increased 340% in the past ten days. Three weeks later, the local crisis line is overwhelmed and two emergency psychiatric holds are filed in the same week. The Social Media Distress Signal Monitor would have flagged the pattern on day three of the surge \'97 not day twenty-one. A community health worker would have been dispatched to host a drop-in session at the neighborhood community center. The warning was always there, written publicly by the people who needed help. The system simply reads it before it becomes a 911 call.",\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3     "possible_information_structure": "The information structure is a ZIP-code-level weekly distress signal record with the following schema: zip_code (string, 5-digit), week_start_date (ISO 8601), week_end_date (ISO 8601), total_posts_analyzed (int), distress_keyword_hit_rate (float, 0-1), sentiment_distress_score (float, 0-1 normalized from NLP model output), week_over_week_change_pct (float), brfss_baseline_poor_mental_health_days (float, CDC anchor), composite_distress_index (float, 0-100 weighted score), alert_threshold_exceeded (boolean), recommended_action (string enum: Monitor / Increase Outreach / Deploy Community Health Worker / Escalate to Crisis Coordinator), data_source (string array listing platforms analyzed). Portability is achieved by using ZIP code as the universal geographic key, ISO dates, and normalized 0-1 scores that any downstream system \'97 from a nonprofit CRM to a city dashboard \'97 can consume without transformation. Delivered as JSON via weekly API push and as CSV for manual review by coordinators."\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3   \},\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3   \{\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3     "idea_rank": 2,\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3     "idea_name": "Mental Health Crisis Early-Warning System: 211 Call Volume Forecaster",\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3     "idea_summary": "The second implementation approach focuses on the 211 crisis call system itself \'97 using historical call volume data, caller demographics, call reason codes, and seasonal patterns to build a time-series forecasting model that predicts when and where call volume will exceed crisis line capacity. SAMHSA public crisis call datasets and city-level 211 call logs are used to train ARIMA and LSTM models that generate 2-4 week ahead forecasts at the county and ZIP code level. The model incorporates leading economic indicators \'97 weekly unemployment insurance claims, SNAP application spikes, utility shutoff notices \'97 as exogenous variables that historically precede mental health call surges. Outputs are staffing recommendations delivered to 211 call center managers and mobile crisis team schedulers ahead of predicted peak periods.",\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3     "information_story": "Every year, the King County crisis line experiences a predictable but always-surprising surge in calls during the two weeks after the holiday season ends. Call center managers know from experience that January is hard \'97 but they do not know which specific week will be the worst, how many extra staff to schedule, or whether this year's surge will be larger or smaller than last year's. In January 2023, the surge arrived four days earlier than expected. Fourteen callers were placed on hold for over thirty minutes. Two hung up and did not call back. The 211 Call Volume Forecaster would have analyzed the prior October's unemployment insurance filing spike in the county \'97 a known 6-week leading indicator \'97 and predicted the surge date within a three-day window. The call center manager would have received a staffing recommendation on December 28th. Those fourteen callers would have reached someone immediately. The data to make this prediction existed inside government databases. What was missing was a model that read it as a signal rather than a statistic.",\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3     "possible_information_structure": "The information structure is a weekly call-volume forecast record at the county and ZIP code level: geography_id (FIPS county code or ZIP), forecast_generated_date (ISO 8601), forecast_target_week_start (ISO 8601), forecast_target_week_end (ISO 8601), historical_avg_weekly_calls (float), predicted_call_volume (int), predicted_vs_capacity_ratio (float, values above 1.0 indicate overflow risk), overflow_risk_tier (string enum: Low / Moderate / High / Critical), leading_indicator_ui_claims_change_pct (float, weekly unemployment insurance delta), leading_indicator_snap_applications_change_pct (float), model_confidence_score (float, 0-1), staffing_recommendation (string: Maintain / Add 1 shift / Add 2 shifts / Activate surge protocol), forecast_model_version (string). The record is designed for direct ingestion by call center workforce management software, city emergency operations platforms, and nonprofit scheduling tools. JSON is the primary delivery format via weekly API; a plain-language summary version is generated as a PDF briefing for non-technical call center managers."\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3   \},\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3   \{\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3     "idea_rank": 3,\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3     "idea_name": "Mental Health Crisis Early-Warning System: Emergency Dispatch + Care Gap Mapper",\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3     "idea_summary": "The third implementation approach focuses on the back end of the crisis pipeline \'97 emergency dispatch logs \'97 and maps them against the supply side of mental health care to identify where crisis demand is already exceeding available services, block by block. City open-data emergency dispatch records are parsed to extract mental-health-related incidents (EMS calls coded as psychiatric emergencies, welfare checks, and police responses to behavioral health situations), then overlaid with a real-time inventory of mental health care availability: crisis bed counts, community mental health center appointment wait times, and mobile crisis team deployment locations. The resulting care gap map shows not just where crises are happening but where people in crisis have nowhere to go \'97 the double-failure zones where demand is highest and supply is lowest. Predictive modeling on dispatch trends generates a 2-week forward projection of which zones will enter critical gap status.",\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3     "information_story": "On a single Friday night in the Central District of Seattle, emergency dispatch logs record eleven mental-health-related calls within a six-block radius. Officers respond to eight of them because no mobile crisis team is available. Of the three people transported to the nearest psychiatric emergency facility, two are turned away because the facility is at 97% capacity and directed to a hospital thirty minutes away. The data for all of this is captured \'97 in dispatch logs, in hospital admission records, in mobile team deployment records \'97 but it is captured in three different systems that never speak to each other. No one ever sees the eleven calls on a map alongside the zero available crisis beds. The Emergency Dispatch and Care Gap Mapper would have shown that six-block zone glowing red on a coordinator's dashboard at 6pm \'97 before the calls started \'97 based on the prior two weeks of dispatch trends and the real-time bed availability feed. A mobile crisis team would have been pre-positioned two blocks away. The system does not predict the future perfectly. It simply makes the present visible in time to act.",\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3     "possible_information_structure": "The information structure is a census-block-group-level care gap record updated daily: census_block_group_fips (string), date (ISO 8601), mental_health_dispatch_incidents_7day (int), mental_health_dispatch_incidents_30day (int), dispatch_trend_7day_change_pct (float), crisis_beds_available_within_5mi (int), mobile_crisis_teams_available_now (int), nearest_community_mental_health_center_wait_days (float), care_gap_score (float, 0-100 computed as demand-to-supply ratio normalized), care_gap_tier (string enum: Adequate / Strained / Gap / Critical Gap), predicted_gap_tier_in_14_days (string enum), recommended_preposition_action (string: No action / Monitor / Pre-position team / Activate mutual aid), data_freshness_dispatch (ISO 8601 timestamp of last dispatch log update), data_freshness_bed_availability (ISO 8601 timestamp of last bed count update). Delivered as GeoJSON for real-time mapping dashboards used by crisis coordinators, as JSON for integration with hospital bed management systems, and as daily CSV digest for city emergency management briefings. FIPS codes ensure the record joins cleanly to Census demographic overlays for equity analysis."\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
